In an age where opinions fly right left and centre, he decided to counter the attack through facts. That's my most significant memory of #ProfSunilKumar. Administrative head second, always a historian first. (4/4)
"Facts have more value than my opinion. You should know why our syllabus is what it is. Read it, and understand it. Call me if you have doubts," he said. (3/n)
He was polite but firm that he wouldn't have a conversation on the phone & called me to the dept. When I went the next day, he simply took out some papers from his drawer and handed them to me. (2/n)

Undoubtedly the most difficult obit I've had to write.  What is not included in this, is my memory of #SunilKumar. During his tenure as HoD in DU, there was an attack on the history syllabus. I had called him to know how the dept was responding (1/n) https://t.co/8YZQGWYEbF

Academically, both focussed on the Indian context , Prof Singh on Indian modernity and tradition and Prof Bhambri on Indian politics, Hindutva etc. They were also both staunch secularists. But the creepiest coincidence is that they both died at the age of 87, and on a Sunday.

Both studied in universities in UP (Lucknow and Agra respectively) and taught in universities in Rajasthan (Jodhpur and Jaipur respectively), before moving to JNU in the 70s as founding professors of their respective depts.
JNU lost two Emeritus Professors this year - Sociologist Yogendra Singh in May and Political Scientist C P Bhambri yesterday. While filing my story yesterday I realised a few similarities.

@WilliamChachu @kainisms A lone police personnel wielding a lathi is not the same as a lathicharge.

Does this mean all police personnel were well-behaved and did not hit a single student? No. But we must be able to draw the distinction between the actions of some police personnel and the police force as a whole. That's a crucial difference that cannot be overlooked.

What is being contested is the claim of injuries caused by police lathicharge. I have been covering protests in Delhi since 2015 now. There are other much more senior colleagues on the beat. We have seen police brutality, in Jamia itself, but today was just not it.

We also did not say that those detained were not or could not have been injured because we weren't at the police station or inside the van to be able to make that claim. We were merely talking about police action at the spot.

Nobody said protesters did not faint or suffocate or get injured. Some of us reporters, who were on the ground (yes that's important) merely said there was no police lathicharge. There was  constant dhakka mukki between the police and protesters which did lead to injuries.
